properties.text1: STATUS: After many months of native-led protest at Standing Rock in 2016, the 1,172-mile-long pipeline was authorized by the incoming Trump administration and currently delivers over half a million barrels of crude oil per day to the Patoka Terminal in Illinois. But on March 25, 2020, as reported in the New York Times, the Standing Rock Sioux Tribe won a suit in a federal court against the Army Corps of Engineers for failure to conduct an adequate environmental review. The next step will be a decision as to whether the oil can continue flowing while a full review is carried out under the provisions of the National Environmental Policy Act.
properties.text3:
ADVOCACY: "After years of commitment to defending our water and earth, we welcome this news of a significant legal win," said Standing Rock Sioux Tribe Chairman Mike Faith. source here.
